**Where the Difference Comes From**

The original SCOAP rule is from Goldsteinâ€™s definition of output controllability: evaluate each justifying input assignment by taking the **sum** of its input controllabilities, then take the **minimum** over the possible justifications, then add cell depth. For **sequential** SCOAP, combinational gates have sequential depth `0`, and flip-flops have sequential depth `1`.  
Source: [Goldstein and Thigpen, DAC 1980](https://www.cs.york.ac.uk/rts/docs/DAC-1964-2006/PAPERS/1980/DAC80_190.PDF), p. 190-191.

The textbook using your figure says the same thing in simpler words: sequential formulas differ from combinational formulas only in that you **do not add `1` across logic levels**; you add `1` only when passing through a flip-flop. It also explicitly states that gate 5â€™s `SC1` becomes `3`.  
Source: [Electronic Testing for VLSI Circuits, Sec. 6.1.3-6.1.4](https://studylib.net/doc/27851539/essentials-of-electronic-testing--soc-)

The `min/max` method is not the original SCOAP recurrence. It comes from a different interpretation:
- â€śHow soon can this value appear if independent requirements are prepared in parallel?â€ť
- If **all** required inputs must be ready, the finish time is the **slowest** one: `max(...)`
- If **any one** input is enough, the finish time is the **earliest** one: `min(...)`

That is why it behaves like a level / arrival-time calculation. The same textbookâ€™s levelization algorithm uses â€śoutput level = maximum input level + 1,â€ť which is the same scheduling intuition.  
Source: [same textbook, levelization discussion](https://studylib.net/doc/27851539/essentials-of-electronic-testing--soc-)

